class Solution {
    private long ans = 0;
    private long total = 0;
    private List<Integer>[] g;
    private int[] values;

    public long maximumScoreAfterOperations(int[][] edges, int[] values) {
        int n = values.length;
        this.values = values;
        g = new ArrayList[n];
        Arrays.setAll(g, e -> new ArrayList<>());
        for (int[] e : edges) {
            int x = e[0], y = e[1];
            g[x].add(y);
            g[y].add(x);
        }
        for (int v : values) {
            total += v;
        }
        dfs(0, -1);
        return ans;
    }

    private long dfs(int x, int fa) {
        if (g[x].size() == 1) {
            return values[x];
        }
        long loss = 0;
        for (int y : g[x]) {
            if (y != fa) {
                loss += dfs(y, x);
            }
        }
        ans = Math.max(ans, (total - loss) * loss);
        return Math.min(values[x], loss);
    }
}
```

In this code, we first create the adjacency list `g` and calculate the total sum of all nodes' values. Then we use depth-first search (dfs) to traverse the tree, in which we calculate the loss of the current node `x`. The loss is the sum of the values of all its descendants plus itself. The score is the product of the total sum minus the loss and the loss. Finally, we return the maximum score.

