class Solution {
    public int minOrAfterOperations(int[] nums, int k) {
        int ans = 0;
        int mask = 0;
        for (int b = 29; b >= 0; b--) {
            mask |= 1 << b;
            int cnt = 0; // operation count
            int and = -1; // -1 in binary has all 1's
            for (int x : nums) {
                and &= x & mask;
                if (and != 0) {
                    cnt++; // merge x, operation count increases
                } else {
                    and = -1; // prepare to merge next segment
                }
            }
            if (cnt > k) {
                ans |= mask; // the corresponding bit of the answer must be 1
                mask ^= 1 << b; // no longer consider this bit in the future
            }
        }
        return ans;
    }
}
```

Please note that the code above implements a greedy algorithm to calculate the minimum possible value of the bitwise OR of the remaining elements of nums after applying at most k operations. It uses a bitmask to represent the possible numbers that can be formed by the bitwise AND operations. It first determines the maximum possible number that can be formed by bitwise AND operations, then checks if the number of operations required to form that number exceeds the limit k. If it does, it means that we cannot form that number, so we set the corresponding bit of the answer to 1 and exclude this bit from the future considerations. The process is repeated until all bits have been checked.

